			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I saw a request for a charming FAQ in the library.. here is my draft version for the library.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Mage Guide to Charming</span>
<br />

<br />
Since there are many types of mages out there with a wide range of AAs, I’ve decided to make a basic guide which describes the techniques needed to charm mobs solo.  At the end of this FAQ there is a listing of the nice to have items and AAs which makes charming easier.
<br />

<br />
REQUIRED:
<br />

<br />
Elemental Silence, MAG 63:  Mesmerize for 30 sec, -10 MR check, Memblur (30%)
<br />

<br />
Call of the Arch Mage, MAG 65:  Charm, MAXIMUM mob level of 60, max duration 20.5 minutes
<br />

<br />

<br />
VERY HELPFUL:
<br />

<br />
- Spell haste items.  Naki’s Summoned Spiked Ring is the most common (MAG 61 summoned spell haste ring).  Blessing of Reverence (CLR 62 spell haste spell which stacks with Naki’s ring).
<br />

<br />
- HP Buffs.  I recommend Shield of Maelin (MAG 64), Xegony’s Phantasmal Guard (MAG 62), and Virtue (CLR 62).  You could substitute Focus of the Seventh (SHM 65), Symbol of Kazad (CLR 61) and Blessing of the Nine (DRU 65) and cancel out our self buffs but I’m a believer in the extra AC that virtue / self buffs provide.  For the record, the difference between Self buffs / Virtue (1755 hp and 153 AC) and Fot7 / Bot9 / Kazad (2072 hp and 32 AC) is 317 hp and 121 AC.  Since 317 hp equates to approximately one hit in places like BoT, I’d rather have the AC and partially mitigate or avoid the damage.
<br />

<br />
- Movement haste.  Spirit of the Eagle (DRU 54, RNG 64), or Spirit of the Wolf + Levitation.
<br />

<br />
- Suspend Minion.  Have a pet up in case of emergencies (or worst case a mob to canni for mana).  Most times the 4 second casting time for suspend minion will mean instant death from a BOV or FB ex-charmed pet.
<br />

<br />
- Shrinking your pet can help you differntiate between your pet and your target (if they have similar models like the iksar golems in Veksar).
<br />

<br />
TECHNIQUES
<br />

<br />
- Tab-Lock.  It is important that your pet be tab-locked.  To do this, target  your pet, hit tab (should target you) then hit tab again to target your pet.  Now whenever you have another mob targeted you can quickly target your pet by hitting ESC (to clear target) then TAB (targets you) and then TAB again (targets pet).  This is useful when charm breaks and you have to quickly mez your pet again.
<br />

<br />
-  Secondary Target.  This is similar to Tab-Lock, but allows you to easily switch between your current target and your last target.  I usually have my pet Tab-Locked and then target the enemy mob so I can easily switch between the pet and the target.
<br />

<br />
- Timer.  Some custom UI allows for timers.  Putting in a timer for the max duration of charm is useful so you can be on the defensive if charm lasts the full 20.5 minutes.
<br />

<br />
- Corner tanking.  Always position yourself in a corner or against a wall so if charm breaks you can mez quickly without getting interrupted.  In most cases the kick / bash of the charmed pet will interrupt  spell casting, but if you position yourself against the wall you have a better chance to channel through it.
<br />

<br />
- Spell Lineup.  I have the following spells up when charming
<br />
     Call of the ArchMage  (to charm)
<br />
     Elemental Silence  (to mez)
<br />
     Malosinia (max debuff)
<br />
     Mala (unresistable debuff)
<br />
     Nuke (to tag enemy mob and gain more exp per kill)
<br />
     Burnout V (haste)
<br />
     Veil of Elements (invis)
<br />
     Gate (to hopefully get away)
<br />

<br />
- Aggro.  Since this guide is intended for soloing only the four person rule doesn’t apply.  This rule simply states that  if more than 4 people engage (or have aggro) on a particular mob then the mob will ignore the charmed pet and attack the PC with the highest aggro.  In this situation, charmed mobs count as a person.  For example, you could have 2 charmers and 2 pets and this would not exceed the 4 people limit.  If you had 2 charmers, 2 pets and a slower the mob would make a beeline to the person with the highest aggro—mostly like the slower.
<br />

<br />
Another aspect of aggro is that charmed pets have an aggro range like PCs do (and unlike our normal pets).  This means that if you bring a charm pet with you it might very well aggro mobs along the way if you are not careful.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Charming!
<br />

<br />
This is where the fun begins.  The first thing you need to do is bind near your charm point.  Until you get the hang of charming, you will die.  Accept this and do not be afraid.  Secondly, you need to find a suitable target that you can cast on without getting aggro from other mobs.  Once you find this mob, do the following:
<br />
-  Cast Elemental Silence (if it is resisted, keep casting it until the mob is mezzed)
<br />
-  Once the mob is mezzed, cast Mala followed by Malosinia.
<br />
-  Charm pet.
<br />
-  Tab-lock your pet.
<br />
-  Type /pet sit.  When you have your pet sit, it gives you a fraction of a second more time to recast Elemental Silence if charm breaks.
<br />
-  Find a target
<br />
-  Cast Burnout V
<br />
-  /pet kill target
<br />
-  Cast nuke on target to gain a higher percentage of exp
<br />

<br />
If your pet’s charm breaks during a fight you can basically zone, Gate or die.  If the target you are fighting summons (likely to happen if you fight in BoT , Veksar, SolC)—zone, Gate or die (the latter being the most common option).
<br />

<br />
Say you have killed a few mobs and your pet’s health is low.  You have a couple of options.  Gate, run back in and then re-mez and re-charm your ex-pet (careful now, he is hasted).  The pet should be at full health because no one is on its aggro list so it will regen quickly.  The other option is to simply cast Elemental Silence in an attempt to memblur (30% chance per cast), wait until it regens (no one is on the hate list) and then re-charm.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Grouping
<br />
- Using a charmed pet in groups is a really effective way to increase the DPS of the party or raid.  The number one thing you want on your pet in a group or raid situation is snare (DRU or RNG).  This allows you to move out of the way when charm breaks to re-mez / re-charm your pet.  This also provides enough safety margin if the area is large that you can haste your pet.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Where to Charm
<br />
- elemental looking mobs in Torden, Bastion of Thunder
<br />
- iksar golems in Veksar
<br />
- stonegrabber models in LDoN Takish-Hiz
<br />
- SolC
<br />

<br />

<br />
NICE TO HAVE
<br />
- Insta-click Invisibility to Animals item from Temple of Solusek Ro quests (allows you to break charm whenever you like and re-mez / re-charm)
<br />
-  Root.  Several insta-click root items available (with charges) that can save you in a dire situation.
<br />

<br />

<br />
AA Guide
<br />
The best AAs to have for charming are basically anything that helps you channel a spell (Channeling Focus, Spell Casting Expertise lvl 1 for Gate), give you more hitpoints (Natural Durability, Elemental Earth Form), or mitigate damage (Combat Agility, Combat Stability, Lightning Reflexes).  Another AA nice to have for maximizing damage is Frenzied Burnout.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Edit:  made changes based on feedback</span><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=653282" target=_blank>Sage Casala, Arch Convoker of Saryrn</a>
<br />
